  "articleSummary": "The article argues that \"generative UI\" is not a single technology but a layered stack—product shell, UI composition model, runtime/transport, and agent/tool backend—and that conflating these layers leads to confusion. It introduces a control spectrum from tool-to-component rendering (safe, developer-owned) to open-ended generated HTML (high agent freedom, risky), recommending the smallest amount of freedom that solves the user problem. The tone is analytical and explanatory, aimed at developers and architects building LLM-powered applications, with recurring metaphors like \"training wheels\" for chat UI and \"soup\" for blurred concepts.",
